         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">26/8/87. ¶  ¶ It is incumbent on me, dear Mr Buchanan, ¶  to tender you my gratefulness for your having named such a handsome Ranunculus after myself. ¶  I feel quite proud of this, particularly as I ...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">87.08.26</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To John Buchanan</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">A644, Mitchell Library, State Library of New South Wales, Sydney.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">26/8/87.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>It is incumbent on me, dear Mr Buchanan,<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>John Buchanan (1819-1898).</p>
               </note> to tender you my gratefulness for your having named such a handsome Ranunculus after myself.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See Buchanan (1887), where <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Ranunculus muelleri</seg> is described on pp. 215-6 and illustrated in plate 16.</p>
               </note> I feel quite proud of this, particularly as I studied in Scandinavia and Germany from 1840-1846 the many species indigenous there. As I should be so sorry, to loose such a beautiful and lasting souvenir of yours, I would suggest that the name be changed to R. Baronis, because an Australian alpine species, discovered by me in 1854 and confirmed by me in 1873, bears already my name.<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>i.e. <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Ranunculus muelleri</seg> in Bentham (1863-78), vol. 1, p. 13. Buchanan's name was not changed as M suggested and is treated as a synonym of <seg style="font-style: italic; ">R. insignia</seg> (<seg style="font-style: italic; ">New Zealand flora</seg> (accessed 15 January 2020)). </p>
               </note> Could you kindly send me a specimen of your supposed <name key="Gastrodia">Gastrodia</name>?<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">
                        <name key="Gastrodia">Gastrodia</name> hectori</seg>, in Buchanan (1887), p. 214, plate 15.</p>
               </note> It is, to judge from your delineation, not a genuine species of that genus, but likely belongs to <name key="Prasophyllum">Prasophyllum</name>, and may not be different from one of several large Austral. species.<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>See <seg style="font-style: italic; ">New Zealand flora</seg> (accessed 15 January 2020).</p>
               </note> Should you have specimens in fl. or fruit of <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">any</hi>
               </seg> N.Z. Ranunculus to spare, I would in <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">your interest</hi>
               </seg> send them to a monographer in Bohemia<note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Karl Prantl? See M to A. Engler, 25 December 1887. The monograph of Ranunculaceae appeared as Prantl (1891a).</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Regardfully your</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Ferd von Mueller.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="plant%20names" xml:lang="en">
               <name key="Gastrodia">Gastrodia</name>
            </p>
